## Project overview
the life Hack or urban Myth App is a native Android quiz application developed using Kotlin in Android study.
the purpose of this app is to help users identify whether common internet life hacks are true productivity tips or simply urban myths.

Users are presented with flashcard-style statements and must choose between:
Hack (True)
Myth (False)

At the end of the quiz, the app calculates the users total score and provides person feedback.


## Purpose and features
This application was created to:
Improve user Knowledge on useful life hacks
Help users distinguish between facts and myths
Provide an engaging quiz experience


### Main Features:
Welcome Screen
Flashcard Question Screen
Immediate Feedback
Score Counter
Final Result Screen
Review Answers Screen

## Design Considerations
The app was designed with a simple and user-friendly interface to ensure easy navigation.

### Design decisions include:
Large readable Button for answer selection
Minimalist screen layout
Clear score display
Easy-to-understand feedback messages

The colour choice and spacing were kept clean to improve user experience.


## Application Logic
The application uses:
A List of question objects stored in QuestionBack.Kt
A Loop system to navigate through each flashcard
Conditional statements to verify user answers
A score variable to count correct responses

After the last question, the app automatically navigates to the Score Screen.


## GitHub and Version Control
GitHub was used to manege all source code versions throughout development.

The following GitHub practices were applied:
Creating a remote repository
Frequent commits after each major chance
Pushing updated code to GitHub

This ensured backup, version history, and project tracking.


##GitHub Actions Automation
GitHub Actions was implement to automatically build and test the Android project whenever code is pushed to the repository.

This helps ensure That:
the application compiles correctly,
there are no broken files,
the project remains functional on all updates.


##Testing and Debugging
Manual testing was performed on all application screens to varify:
Button clicks
screen navigation
Correct answer checking
Review functionality

Logcat logging was also used during development for debugging purposes.

